Given that no static polarization anisotropy is observable in our samples, we consider the local polarization of such nanoregions to be randomly oriented in space. We now discuss how excitation of such an isotropic distribution of polarized structures leads to overall polarization anisotropy. The theoretically calculated anisotropy in absorption is imprinted onto the carrier populations upon optical excitation. The total transient absorption signal for a sample containing many polarized nanoregions can be written in a condensed form as2α= ∑i∈NRΠi×ni,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
