Our theoretical model above assumes an isotropic distribution of carrier momenta shortly after photoexcitation—i.e., that thermalization and cooling processes randomize carrier momentum on approximately 200 fs time scales40. This is likely to hold for excitations with more than approximately 100 meV excess energy above the band edge, for which the excitation isosurface is approximately spherical (Fig. 6c, isosurface plot, high energy). However, excitations close to the band edge access a restricted momentum space, since the presence of polar distortions leads to toroidal isosurfaces (Fig. 6d, isosurface plot, low energy). To demonstrate how the changes in the momentum space distribution with energy affect transient absorption, we write the transient absorption signal for a single nanoregion i as an integral over momentum space:4αi=∫Sd3kΠik⃗ni(k⃗)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
